00:00:45.490 --> 00:00:48.630
But before we dive in
and get into specifics,

00:00:48.630 --> 00:00:51.310
we wanted to start
with just some basics--

00:00:51.310 --> 00:00:56.670
what is accessibility, inclusive
design, and why it's important.

00:00:56.670 --> 00:00:59.670
As described by the Web
Accessibility Initiative,

00:00:59.670 --> 00:01:03.930
accessibility, usability,
and inclusive design

00:01:03.930 --> 00:01:06.730
are all very closely related.

00:01:06.730 --> 00:01:11.010
Their goals, approaches,
and guidelines

00:01:11.010 --> 00:01:13.080
overlap significantly.

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:16.260
And when we sit down to
design and develop our apps,

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:21.560
it's really effective to
address them together.

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:23.660
Let's start with accessibility.

00:01:23.660 --> 00:01:27.400
Accessibility focuses
on enabling users

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:34.330
with disabilities to perceive,
interact, understand,

00:01:34.330 --> 00:01:38.350
and navigate tools and
services and products,

00:01:38.350 --> 00:01:43.220
and that they can contribute
equally without barriers.

00:01:43.220 --> 00:01:46.120
Now, some of the guidelines we
think about with accessibility,

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:52.090
such as clear color contrast
or clear, concise writing,

00:01:52.090 --> 00:01:55.390
are useful not only to
users with disabilities

00:01:55.390 --> 00:01:57.942
but also those that might be--

00:01:57.942 --> 00:01:59.650
or that don't have
disabilities but might

00:01:59.650 --> 00:02:02.070
be in different situations.

00:02:02.070 --> 00:02:05.780
For example, we know
that alternative text

00:02:05.780 --> 00:02:09.680
can be useful to users who are
blind and can't see the screen,

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:13.430
as it describes the
imagery and visual icons.

00:02:13.430 --> 00:02:17.060
Alternative text can
also be useful to users

00:02:17.060 --> 00:02:21.290
who might be out in remote
locations with low bandwidth

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:24.510
or using old technology.

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:28.970
Another example-- it's clear
that providing enough time

00:02:28.970 --> 00:02:34.160
for users to interact with
and read content on the screen

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:37.700
is useful for users who
might have a motor impairment

00:02:37.700 --> 00:02:39.620
or cognitive impairment.

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:43.760
This extra time is also
very useful for users

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:46.340
that might be learning
a new language

00:02:46.340 --> 00:02:50.570
or have low literacy, or
children learning to read,

00:02:50.570 --> 00:02:53.830
or simply just
people distracted.

00:02:53.830 --> 00:02:58.540
And this is how accessibility
is a key component

00:02:58.540 --> 00:03:00.760
of inclusive design.

00:03:00.760 --> 00:03:07.750
Inclusive design is all about
considering the wide range

00:03:07.750 --> 00:03:09.880
of human abilities.

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:17.060
We think of age, gender,
ethnicity, and others.

00:03:17.060 --> 00:03:19.090
And as you can
see, accessibility

00:03:19.090 --> 00:03:22.820
overlaps significantly
with these areas as well.

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:25.570
And that's why we feel
like accessibility is

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:30.100
a really clear starting point.

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:34.120
So at this point, we could
just throw up on the screen

00:03:34.120 --> 00:03:35.640
a checklist of
guidelines for you

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:38.860
to follow to ensure that
your product is accessible.

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:42.080
And that's a great place to
start, no doubt about it.

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:46.320
However, what we've
seen is that may often

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:51.690
lead to a product that's
technically accessible but not

00:03:51.690 --> 00:03:57.640
necessarily usable, let alone a
great experience for all users.

00:03:57.640 --> 00:04:02.440
And this is where
usability comes into play.

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:04.650
Now how many people, by
a quick show of hands,

00:04:04.650 --> 00:04:08.250
take time to reach out and get
feedback and input from users?

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:09.540
Quick show of hands-- right.

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:13.140
It's an important and really
useful thing to do, right?

00:04:13.140 --> 00:04:18.149
Unfortunately, we know that a
lot of users with disabilities

00:04:18.149 --> 00:04:22.830
are left out of this really key
critical point in the process.

00:04:22.830 --> 00:04:27.660
If we're not out there talking
and observing our users,

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:33.720
we'll never understand, what
are their true experiences?

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:35.010
What are their challenges?

00:04:39.890 --> 00:04:42.470
And most importantly,
what are their insights

00:04:42.470 --> 00:04:45.300
that could actually
benefit everyone?

00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:48.050
And in the end, you
could be left missing out

00:04:48.050 --> 00:04:52.040
on a large number
of potential users

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:55.370
and also miss out on helping
existing users who might be

00:04:55.370 --> 00:04:58.510
in these limiting situations.

00:04:58.510 --> 00:05:00.510
OK, so that's the basics.

00:05:00.510 --> 00:05:03.960
We've got the stage set.

00:05:03.960 --> 00:05:06.960
Now, we want to walk you
through more of a case study

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:09.210
to demonstrate how
to design and develop

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:10.530
with accessibility in mind.

00:05:13.850 --> 00:05:15.700
Today, we're going to
use our fictional app.

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:19.032
It's a travel and
hospitality app called Crane.

00:05:19.032 --> 00:05:21.490
And we're going to use this
throughout the rest of the talk

00:05:21.490 --> 00:05:24.190
to demonstrate specifics of
how to make products more

00:05:24.190 --> 00:05:27.770
inclusive using the standard
user-centered design

00:05:27.770 --> 00:05:32.860
methodologies, as well as
material design system, which

00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:36.050
includes clear guidelines,
components, and tooling.

00:05:40.070 --> 00:05:42.740
So to get this started,
we're going to break it down

00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:45.560
into four primary stages.

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:50.910
We have defining the product
vision, design, development,

00:05:50.910 --> 00:05:52.640
and after design.

00:05:52.640 --> 00:05:55.280
Now, this framework probably
seems familiar to you,

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:56.480
and that's on purpose.

00:05:56.480 --> 00:05:59.750
We're not here to introduce
yet another process for you

00:05:59.750 --> 00:06:01.320
to follow.

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:04.280
Instead, we see this as a
tool kit of ideas and things

00:06:04.280 --> 00:06:07.340
that you can do to
enhance your product

00:06:07.340 --> 00:06:11.530
to make it more inclusive,
because in the end,

00:06:11.530 --> 00:06:18.184
inclusive design is really
just simply good design.

00:06:18.184 --> 00:06:20.600
OK, so now Andrea is going to
walk through the first stage

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:23.259
of defining the product vision.

00:06:23.259 --> 00:06:24.300
ANDREA WONG: Thanks, Jen.

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:30.460
Stage one, defining
the product vision.

00:06:30.460 --> 00:06:33.310
No matter what you're
building, understanding

00:06:33.310 --> 00:06:35.710
what problems you're
solving for users

00:06:35.710 --> 00:06:38.590
is the key to product success.

00:06:38.590 --> 00:06:41.950
So who are your users?

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:43.900
Most teams start
with the assumption

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:46.930
that all their users
are fully-abled,

00:06:46.930 --> 00:06:49.760
but that may not
always be the case.

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:52.780
So let's say you're
building a photos app.

00:06:52.780 --> 00:06:55.600
And you think, well, why
would someone who is blind

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:57.820
use my photos app?

00:06:57.820 --> 00:07:01.570
Actually, a person who
is blind may use your app

00:07:01.570 --> 00:07:04.180
because they want to
take photos and then

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:06.490
share them with
friends and families

00:07:06.490 --> 00:07:12.060
or post them on social media,
just like everyone else.

00:07:12.060 --> 00:07:15.200
Consider these three
people on the screen.

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:18.470
There's a man in a wheelchair
with Lou Gehrig's disease.

00:07:18.470 --> 00:07:20.035
So he has impaired
motor functioning

00:07:20.035 --> 00:07:22.000
for upper and lower body.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.040
There's a boy with a broken arm.

00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:27.490
And there's a woman holding
a full bag of groceries.

00:07:27.490 --> 00:07:30.410
Let's have a pop quiz.

00:07:30.410 --> 00:07:33.730
Which of these three people
have limited mobility.

00:07:33.730 --> 00:07:36.690
Raise their hand if you think
it's the man in the wheelchair.

00:07:40.190 --> 00:07:42.200
OK, hands down.

00:07:42.200 --> 00:07:44.280
Raise your hand if you
think it's the boy.

00:07:47.900 --> 00:07:48.850
Thank you.

00:07:48.850 --> 00:07:51.360
And lastly, raise your hand
if you think it's the woman.

00:07:55.380 --> 00:08:02.090
So if you raised your hands all
three times, you're correct.

00:08:02.090 --> 00:08:05.990
All three of them have
a different relationship

00:08:05.990 --> 00:08:08.600
with limited mobility,
whether it's permanent,

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:13.070
like the man; temporary,
like the boy; or situational,

00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:14.950
like the woman
with the groceries.

00:08:14.950 --> 00:08:19.520
Yet, they're all experiencing
the exact same need right now.

00:08:19.520 --> 00:08:23.240
It's a good reminder that
for every single one of us,

00:08:23.240 --> 00:08:25.940
we'll have accessibility
needs at some point

00:08:25.940 --> 00:08:27.990
throughout our lifetime.

00:08:27.990 --> 00:08:33.240
Disability is a much broader
term than we might think.

00:08:33.240 --> 00:08:36.090
And often, when something
doesn't work well

00:08:36.090 --> 00:08:39.510
for a user with no
disabilities, that pain point

00:08:39.510 --> 00:08:42.929
is amplified for people
with disabilities.

00:08:42.929 --> 00:08:45.060
And that's actually
good news for you,

00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:47.730
because it gives you much
clearer signals of what

00:08:47.730 --> 00:08:49.350
you should be focusing on.

00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:51.900
Because when everything doesn't
work-- when something doesn't

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:54.330
work for everyone, it
clearly is something

00:08:54.330 --> 00:08:56.915
that you should be
paying attention to.

00:08:56.915 --> 00:08:59.040
And that's, in fact, what
we found with our studies

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:00.660
at Google.

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:04.410
All users have the same core
needs because they're all

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:07.380
trying to meet the
same goal, whether it's

00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:10.590
sending a photograph,
writing a email,

00:09:10.590 --> 00:09:14.090
buying CryptoKitties,
whatever it is.

00:09:14.090 --> 00:09:16.440
So at this point, you're
probably asking, well,

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:19.770
how do I do research with
people with disabilities?

00:09:19.770 --> 00:09:24.060
The answer is do
what you usually do.

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:26.340
Are you, let's say
in the early stage

00:09:26.340 --> 00:09:29.460
right now, where you're
just chatting and sitting

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:31.310
down and talking to users?

00:09:31.310 --> 00:09:34.950
If you are, that's actually
the easiest and the best time

00:09:34.950 --> 00:09:38.400
to be including users with
disabilities into your process,

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:41.670
because you can get their
context, their needs,

00:09:41.670 --> 00:09:45.990
and everything right
from the very start.

00:09:45.990 --> 00:09:47.820
You can ask the
exact same questions

00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:51.030
as you would to someone
without disabilities.

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:53.730
The only difference
is you have to ask

00:09:53.730 --> 00:09:57.270
a few additional questions about
this assistive technologies

00:09:57.270 --> 00:09:59.940
they may be using and
their context of use.

00:09:59.940 --> 00:10:04.050
So for example,
you'll be asking, say,

00:10:04.050 --> 00:10:06.300
how do you use your
assistive technologies

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:09.150
when you're navigating
a mobile device?

00:10:09.150 --> 00:10:11.250
Or how does your
impairment impact

00:10:11.250 --> 00:10:16.220
or not impact your interactions
when you're planning travel?

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:18.980
Or maybe even, which
workarounds, if any,

00:10:18.980 --> 00:10:21.590
do you use to get
to what you need?

00:10:21.590 --> 00:10:26.450
And always, always follow
up after each question with,

00:10:26.450 --> 00:10:29.600
why, tell me more,
to really dig in

00:10:29.600 --> 00:10:32.580
there to get to the
context of their needs.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:34.890
The bonus here is
their answers may

00:10:34.890 --> 00:10:38.040
inspire new ways of
interactions they've never

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:40.690
thought of before.

00:10:40.690 --> 00:10:43.000
Or maybe you're past
that stage already.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:44.170
That's fine.

00:10:44.170 --> 00:10:49.430
Right now, you're testing a
low-fidelity paper prototype.

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:50.430
That's fine.

00:10:50.430 --> 00:10:54.410
You can still test with
people with disabilities.

00:10:54.410 --> 00:10:58.420
Let's say you're testing with
a user who is blind and uses

00:10:58.420 --> 00:11:01.960
a screen reader, which is an
assistive at the technology

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:04.690
that reads out loud the
contents on the screen.

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:06.910
So you're doing that, but
you don't have a screen

00:11:06.910 --> 00:11:09.350
reader-friendly prototype.

00:11:09.350 --> 00:11:11.170
What you can do here,
though, is write

00:11:11.170 --> 00:11:12.940
a script of what the
screen reader might

00:11:12.940 --> 00:11:16.180
verbalize and have
someone on your team act

00:11:16.180 --> 00:11:18.010
as a screen reader.

00:11:18.010 --> 00:11:21.400
And that person can read each
step out loud to the user

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:24.620
as they walk through the user
flow during the study session.

00:11:27.390 --> 00:11:32.000
By integrating people with
disabilities, whenever you're

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.550
talking to people
without disabilities,

00:11:34.550 --> 00:11:37.610
you're automatically ensuring
that their viewpoints will

00:11:37.610 --> 00:11:40.400
be included and
part of the process

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:42.780
throughout the entire design
and the development phases.

00:11:46.120 --> 00:11:48.670
Along with understanding
user needs,

00:11:48.670 --> 00:11:50.860
you need to have a
general comprehension

00:11:50.860 --> 00:11:54.280
of assistive technologies
and the different tools

00:11:54.280 --> 00:11:57.980
that people may use
interact with your product.

00:11:57.980 --> 00:12:02.310
Trying the technologies yourself
is a great place to start,

00:12:02.310 --> 00:12:07.350
but the best way to learn is
to observe the real experts.

00:12:07.350 --> 00:12:09.870
Those are the people who
use these technologies day

00:12:09.870 --> 00:12:11.740
in and day out.

00:12:11.740 --> 00:12:14.160
And if you can't find someone
to observe in real life,

00:12:14.160 --> 00:12:16.240
that's OK.

00:12:16.240 --> 00:12:20.020
You can just go online and ask--
look for any kind of video.

00:12:20.020 --> 00:12:21.479
Whether it's like
going to the ATM,

00:12:21.479 --> 00:12:22.853
going to the
grocery store, there

00:12:22.853 --> 00:12:24.310
are countless
great videos online

00:12:24.310 --> 00:12:26.440
to explain the different
ways people use

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:28.630
different technologies.

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:30.910
The goal here is
to understand what

00:12:30.910 --> 00:12:34.900
makes a good versus a
poor experience, what

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:37.930
are the common pitfalls, and
the standard expectations

00:12:37.930 --> 00:12:42.310
that people have when
using your site or app.

00:12:42.310 --> 00:12:45.340
Later, using our fictional
app, Crane, we'll

00:12:45.340 --> 00:12:48.370
walk you through designing
a great keyboard navigation

00:12:48.370 --> 00:12:49.780
model.

00:12:49.780 --> 00:12:53.200
Starting with a keyboard
navigation model

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:55.702
creates a very good
foundation for you

00:12:55.702 --> 00:12:57.910
when building for other
assistive technologies, which

00:12:57.910 --> 00:12:58.900
we won't go into here.

00:13:01.660 --> 00:13:03.880
You may be feeling a bit
overwhelmed right now at how

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:06.320
to design to meet
all those needs,

00:13:06.320 --> 00:13:08.440
but the great thing
about design inclusively

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:10.810
is that people on
teams have been working

00:13:10.810 --> 00:13:14.020
for years to understand what
design inclusively actually

00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:15.690
means.

00:13:15.690 --> 00:13:18.890
So as Jen mentioned,
material design components

00:13:18.890 --> 00:13:21.120
includes accessibility
guidelines

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:24.459
baked right in that anyone
can follow, regardless

00:13:24.459 --> 00:13:25.500
of the size of your team.

00:13:28.240 --> 00:13:30.100
Doing the right
thing, though, isn't

00:13:30.100 --> 00:13:34.450
necessarily mutually exclusive
to good business sense either.

00:13:34.450 --> 00:13:37.030
It could even increase
your market share.

00:13:37.030 --> 00:13:39.520
According to the American
Institute of Research,

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:42.460
who came out with this
report a few months ago,

00:13:42.460 --> 00:13:45.730
working-age people with
disabilities in the US

00:13:45.730 --> 00:13:53.230
alone have a discretionary
income of $21 billion.

00:13:53.230 --> 00:13:58.290
That's the third largest market
segment in the entire country.

00:13:58.290 --> 00:14:01.500
Then, if you think about
their families and friends who

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:05.910
may also use your product to
interact with them, or they

00:14:05.910 --> 00:14:08.930
may just simply
appreciate good design.

00:14:08.930 --> 00:14:11.930
And this is not
just the US alone.

00:14:11.930 --> 00:14:15.620
According to Gartner,
people with disabilities

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:18.710
and their friends
and family worldwide

00:14:18.710 --> 00:14:25.822
have a collective disposable
income of $8 trillion dollars.

00:14:25.822 --> 00:14:26.530
Think about that.

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:32.720
OK, that was a lot
of information,

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:36.240
so let's go over the important
points to keep in mind.

00:14:36.240 --> 00:14:39.340
One, talk to people
with disabilities

00:14:39.340 --> 00:14:41.568
to inform your product vision.

00:14:41.568 --> 00:14:46.320
Two, learn assistive
technologies from the experts.

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:50.180
And three, build a better
experience for all users

00:14:50.180 --> 00:14:53.237
and potentially capture
more market share.

00:14:53.237 --> 00:14:55.570
Now, I'm going to hand it
over to Catherine, who's going

00:14:55.570 --> 00:14:57.882
to go over stage two, design.

00:14:57.882 --> 00:14:59.090
CATHERINE IDYLLE: Right here.

