Hi.

00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:10.300
Now that you've defined
your product vision,

00:15:10.300 --> 00:15:12.700
it's time to design your app.

00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:14.290
At this stage,
you'll need to think

00:15:14.290 --> 00:15:19.900
about interaction design, visual
design, UX writing, and motion

00:15:19.900 --> 00:15:20.980
design.

00:15:20.980 --> 00:15:22.090
But don't worry.

00:15:22.090 --> 00:15:24.430
We'll do a design
challenge together

00:15:24.430 --> 00:15:29.060
using our fictional app,
Crane, to learn how to do this.

00:15:29.060 --> 00:15:32.750
So Crane is a travel
and hospitality app

00:15:32.750 --> 00:15:36.860
that lets users book flights
and accommodations on a computer

00:15:36.860 --> 00:15:39.490
or phone.

00:15:39.490 --> 00:15:41.350
In terms of
interaction design, you

00:15:41.350 --> 00:15:43.180
might be wondering,
how do I even

00:15:43.180 --> 00:15:47.140
get started design accessible
and usable experience

00:15:47.140 --> 00:15:48.400
for everyone?

00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:50.830
Well, design as you normally do.

00:15:50.830 --> 00:15:53.050
Have your wireframes
and your sketches,

00:15:53.050 --> 00:15:56.080
and we'll get started there.

00:15:56.080 --> 00:15:59.740
This is a wireframe of filter
options on mobile when you

00:15:59.740 --> 00:16:02.170
search for a flight on Crane.

00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:04.870
Here, we can see that
the checkboxes are

00:16:04.870 --> 00:16:09.400
aligned with the label, but
they're pretty far apart.

00:16:09.400 --> 00:16:12.850
When designing your layout,
ensured that related content

00:16:12.850 --> 00:16:16.010
and controls are
grouped together.

00:16:16.010 --> 00:16:18.350
This makes it
easier to understand

00:16:18.350 --> 00:16:22.400
and also easier to reach for
people with motor disabilities,

00:16:22.400 --> 00:16:27.760
especially for people with ALS
or a traveler on a bumpy train.

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:30.910
So what we did here is that
we placed the checkboxes

00:16:30.910 --> 00:16:32.920
right next to the labels.

00:16:32.920 --> 00:16:36.820
It's just a better
experience for everyone.

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:39.970
In terms of
interaction design, you

00:16:39.970 --> 00:16:43.360
can also have a huge
impact on all users

00:16:43.360 --> 00:16:46.630
by thinking about the
tab interaction model,

00:16:46.630 --> 00:16:49.840
meaning a great
keyboard experience.

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:55.120
Here, we have a wireframe on web
of the flight search results.

00:16:55.120 --> 00:16:58.570
Tabbing on the keyboard
allows you to jump from one

00:16:58.570 --> 00:17:00.940
interactive element
on the screen,

00:17:00.940 --> 00:17:03.500
as we can see right here.

00:17:03.500 --> 00:17:06.040
This would be the
default tab experience

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:08.260
if we didn't design it at all.

00:17:08.260 --> 00:17:12.520
It would take 94
tabs stops to go

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:18.369
from point A, the back button,
to point B, the filter options.

00:17:18.369 --> 00:17:21.310
This is a slow experience.

00:17:21.310 --> 00:17:25.800
So what we can do is
actually group major elements

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:29.880
together, like this list
of individual flights.

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:36.930
Now, it only takes seven
tab stops to reach point B.

00:17:36.930 --> 00:17:40.510
And once you've grouped
your big tab stops together,

00:17:40.510 --> 00:17:43.140
don't forget how to
quickly navigate to those

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:47.080
smaller elements, such
as the individual flights

00:17:47.080 --> 00:17:49.440
in this big list of flights.

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:53.400
Here, we'll go with an
up and down arrow option

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:56.080
to navigate between them.

00:17:56.080 --> 00:18:01.270
Overall, this is a much better
and productive experience

00:18:01.270 --> 00:18:04.960
for power users, much like
yourselves right here,

00:18:04.960 --> 00:18:07.300
and assistive tech users alike.

00:18:09.890 --> 00:18:11.960
Here are some things
you can do to make

00:18:11.960 --> 00:18:16.550
your app more accessible in
terms of interaction design.

00:18:16.550 --> 00:18:20.750
Group your content and
your controls together.

00:18:20.750 --> 00:18:23.710
Design your tab
interaction model.

00:18:23.710 --> 00:18:27.180
And don't forget the
error navigation as well.

00:18:27.180 --> 00:18:30.736
Now, onto Bethany to
talk about visual design.

00:18:30.736 --> 00:18:33.592
[APPLAUSE]

00:18:35.980 --> 00:18:37.480
BETHANY FONG: Thanks, Catherine.

00:18:37.480 --> 00:18:39.190
So now that we've
laid a good foundation

00:18:39.190 --> 00:18:42.640
in terms of interaction design,
let's refine our visuals.

00:18:42.640 --> 00:18:44.590
Now, to start with
the very basics,

00:18:44.590 --> 00:18:48.060
I'm sure you all have felt the
pain of viewing light gray text

00:18:48.060 --> 00:18:49.900
on light gray background.

00:18:49.900 --> 00:18:52.520
Let's not put our
users through that.

00:18:52.520 --> 00:18:55.780
So the number one way that you
can be a hero for these users

00:18:55.780 --> 00:18:58.030
is by ensuring that
color contrast is--

00:18:58.030 --> 00:19:00.250
between your foreground and
your background colors is

00:19:00.250 --> 00:19:01.720
going to be high enough.

00:19:01.720 --> 00:19:03.610
And you can use our
material color tool,

00:19:03.610 --> 00:19:06.946
pictured here, to check the
legibility of your choices

00:19:06.946 --> 00:19:09.070
and check them against
different background colors,

00:19:09.070 --> 00:19:11.830
like the three shades of purple
here that we were exploring

00:19:11.830 --> 00:19:14.510
for the Crane app.

00:19:14.510 --> 00:19:15.999
So let's apply this.

00:19:15.999 --> 00:19:17.540
Going back to our
app, where the user

00:19:17.540 --> 00:19:20.510
is filling in their information
to purchase their flight,

00:19:20.510 --> 00:19:23.450
these faded colors that
you see are trendy,

00:19:23.450 --> 00:19:25.730
but the contrast
is so low that it's

00:19:25.730 --> 00:19:28.220
hard for even most
sighted users to have

00:19:28.220 --> 00:19:30.360
a legible experience here.

00:19:30.360 --> 00:19:33.710
And remember, this is going to
be better not just for users

00:19:33.710 --> 00:19:36.740
with low vision but
someone with dilated eyes

00:19:36.740 --> 00:19:38.840
after a doctor's
appointment or people

00:19:38.840 --> 00:19:41.150
like yourselves, out
in the sun all day

00:19:41.150 --> 00:19:43.130
with glare on your screen.

00:19:43.130 --> 00:19:44.990
So let's add more
color contrast.

00:19:47.710 --> 00:19:50.570
First, we're going to zoom
in on how we can add contrast

00:19:50.570 --> 00:19:52.600
into the text field component.

00:19:52.600 --> 00:19:55.450
We increase the font
weight and color darkness

00:19:55.450 --> 00:19:58.480
in the text fields, which
makes it easier to scan

00:19:58.480 --> 00:20:01.750
and ensures a better
visual hierarchy.

00:20:01.750 --> 00:20:04.430
And we also increase the
background color darkness

00:20:04.430 --> 00:20:07.880
on the button at the bottom,
making the text more legible

00:20:07.880 --> 00:20:10.550
and making the
call-to-action much easier

00:20:10.550 --> 00:20:12.475
to spot, which is
really important,

00:20:12.475 --> 00:20:14.600
because you're trying to
get your users to purchase

00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:16.830
something here.

00:20:16.830 --> 00:20:18.810
And already with the
before and after,

00:20:18.810 --> 00:20:21.570
you can see that this
is a much better design.

00:20:21.570 --> 00:20:24.360
Other than just looking
more aesthetically pleasing,

00:20:24.360 --> 00:20:25.990
the text is more legible.

00:20:25.990 --> 00:20:28.590
The relative importance
of elements is clearer.

00:20:28.590 --> 00:20:32.780
And the call-to-action
are a lot easier to spot.

00:20:32.780 --> 00:20:35.470
So now, your user is
filling in their information

00:20:35.470 --> 00:20:37.690
into those much
better text fields

00:20:37.690 --> 00:20:40.030
and is getting closer
to booking that flight.

00:20:40.030 --> 00:20:42.160
But it looks like
they made an error.

00:20:42.160 --> 00:20:45.890
Some users can tell because
of the bolded orange outline.

00:20:45.890 --> 00:20:48.670
However, some users
with color blindness

00:20:48.670 --> 00:20:51.460
might miss this important
piece of information,

00:20:51.460 --> 00:20:53.170
and this can be fixed
by supplementing

00:20:53.170 --> 00:20:56.530
any information that's coded
in color through other means,

00:20:56.530 --> 00:20:59.140
like icons or shapes.

00:20:59.140 --> 00:21:01.810
So we're going to check
out the material icon site

00:21:01.810 --> 00:21:03.670
and search for error icons.

00:21:03.670 --> 00:21:05.670
It's good to use a central
resource like this,

00:21:05.670 --> 00:21:08.410
because these are common
visual metaphors that

00:21:08.410 --> 00:21:11.860
may be recognizable to
a wide variety of users.

00:21:11.860 --> 00:21:14.550
So it looks like we can
go ahead and use this one.

00:21:14.550 --> 00:21:18.460
So we're going to download
it, add it to our text field,

00:21:18.460 --> 00:21:20.230
and now, there are
two ways to understand

00:21:20.230 --> 00:21:21.610
that this is an error state.

00:21:21.610 --> 00:21:24.190
And this makes it clearer
for everyone, not just

00:21:24.190 --> 00:21:27.010
users who are color blind.

00:21:27.010 --> 00:21:29.180
And for our last
visual design example,

00:21:29.180 --> 00:21:32.840
let's look at focus state
and element size on screen.

00:21:32.840 --> 00:21:35.950
So when users choose a
seat in this travel app,

00:21:35.950 --> 00:21:38.620
it's important that they can
select the seat that they want

00:21:38.620 --> 00:21:41.720
and that they know that their
selection was successful.

00:21:41.720 --> 00:21:43.900
And on mobile, this means
having a touch target

00:21:43.900 --> 00:21:48.530
size of 48 dp by 48 dp, or
about seven millimeters wide,

00:21:48.530 --> 00:21:51.690
which is calibrated against
the size of an adult fingertip.

00:21:51.690 --> 00:21:53.593
Makes sense.

00:21:53.593 --> 00:21:57.660
And on web, try to ensure that
your focus is highly visible.

00:21:57.660 --> 00:22:00.700
You can see it as a bold
purple outline around seat 8A.

00:22:03.490 --> 00:22:05.997
So when you're doing
your visual design,

00:22:05.997 --> 00:22:08.580
when keeping it accessible, make
sure that you have high color

00:22:08.580 --> 00:22:09.720
contrast.

00:22:09.720 --> 00:22:12.210
Make sure that you have
multiple visible indicators

00:22:12.210 --> 00:22:14.490
for any important
component states.

00:22:14.490 --> 00:22:16.330
And lastly, make sure
that your touch target

00:22:16.330 --> 00:22:17.746
sizes are going
to be large enough

00:22:17.746 --> 00:22:20.600
for people to actually reach.

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:22.871
Back over to Catherine.

00:22:22.871 --> 00:22:24.302
[APPLAUSE]

00:22:24.302 --> 00:22:26.250
CATHERINE IDYLLE:
Thanks, Bethany.

00:22:26.250 --> 00:22:28.610
I'm back.

00:22:28.610 --> 00:22:31.640
With writing, you have the
power to guide all users

00:22:31.640 --> 00:22:34.490
with accessible onscreen
text, as well as

00:22:34.490 --> 00:22:36.380
meaningful off-screen
text that'll

00:22:36.380 --> 00:22:39.380
be verbalized by
the screen reader.

00:22:39.380 --> 00:22:41.270
A screen reader is
software that sits

00:22:41.270 --> 00:22:44.810
between you and the application,
and it works in tandem

00:22:44.810 --> 00:22:46.440
with the keyboard.

00:22:46.440 --> 00:22:49.280
The keyboard moves the
focus, and the screen reader

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:53.000
will verbalize whatever
has come into focus.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.160
We have this example
from Google.org com,

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:57.890
if you heard of it, and
it'll read this button

00:22:57.890 --> 00:23:00.800
as Google Search button.

00:23:00.800 --> 00:23:03.470
Because a screen reader
automatically reads out loud

00:23:03.470 --> 00:23:09.050
the label, Google Search,
and the control type, button.

00:23:09.050 --> 00:23:11.060
So back to our Crane app.

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:12.590
Here we have a checkout screen.

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:15.090
It has several
interactive elements,

00:23:15.090 --> 00:23:17.750
but let's just focus
on these four buttons.

00:23:17.750 --> 00:23:20.360
And remember, the screen
reader automatically

00:23:20.360 --> 00:23:22.640
reads out loud the control type.

00:23:22.640 --> 00:23:28.790
So it'll verbalize these buttons
as button, button, button,

00:23:28.790 --> 00:23:30.170
button.

00:23:30.170 --> 00:23:31.920
That's problematic.

00:23:31.920 --> 00:23:33.860
We don't know what
the buttons will do,

00:23:33.860 --> 00:23:37.580
and the council order and
complete order actions

00:23:37.580 --> 00:23:39.440
are right next to
each other, which

00:23:39.440 --> 00:23:42.650
could lead to major user error.

00:23:42.650 --> 00:23:47.380
Instead, what we can do is
add meaningful and concise

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:50.870
accessory labels in addition
to the default button

00:23:50.870 --> 00:23:52.430
verbalization.

00:23:52.430 --> 00:23:57.320
So here, we've added Previous
Step, Checkout Progress, Cancel

00:23:57.320 --> 00:24:00.020
Order, and Checkout Order.

00:24:00.020 --> 00:24:02.570
Now, we know what
each button will do,

00:24:02.570 --> 00:24:07.010
and there won't be a major gaffe
of canceling order rather than

00:24:07.010 --> 00:24:11.760
completing one, and vice versa.

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:15.020
You can be a champion
for screen reader users

00:24:15.020 --> 00:24:18.260
by writing accessory
labels in addition

00:24:18.260 --> 00:24:21.365
to the default verbalization
provided by screen readers.

00:24:24.080 --> 00:24:27.350
In terms of motion
design, have you

00:24:27.350 --> 00:24:31.100
had something important
flash before your eyes,

00:24:31.100 --> 00:24:33.180
blink, and then be gone?

00:24:33.180 --> 00:24:36.470
Well, this just happened to
you and is a major pain point

00:24:36.470 --> 00:24:38.930
for users with low
vision or someone

00:24:38.930 --> 00:24:41.740
who isn't paying attention.

00:24:41.740 --> 00:24:44.520
Try to ensure that
alerts, like snack bars,

00:24:44.520 --> 00:24:47.640
are present on the screen long
enough so that everyone can see

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:50.370
them, like right now,
and have an option

00:24:50.370 --> 00:24:54.240
to easily dismiss them, like
dismiss button or a tapping out

00:24:54.240 --> 00:24:56.160
function.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:25:00.840
Likewise, consider supporting
screen magnification users.

00:25:00.840 --> 00:25:03.780
Here on web, when a
user hovers over a seat,

00:25:03.780 --> 00:25:07.040
they get additional information
about that seat in a hover

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:12.030
card, but it covers the rest
of the screen when magnified.

00:25:12.030 --> 00:25:15.480
To help our users get back
to whatever they were doing,

00:25:15.480 --> 00:25:20.550
consider an easy escape hatch,
such as an escape key shortcut

00:25:20.550 --> 00:25:21.870
or a close button.

00:25:24.480 --> 00:25:27.420
To ensure that your
motion design accessible,

00:25:27.420 --> 00:25:30.300
present alerts for long
enough, and have an option

00:25:30.300 --> 00:25:32.530
to easily dismiss them.

00:25:32.530 --> 00:25:36.030
Likewise, easily escape
hover information

00:25:36.030 --> 00:25:37.570
during screening magnification.

00:25:41.390 --> 00:25:46.190
At this stage, we have designed
the interactive, visual,

00:25:46.190 --> 00:25:50.690
writing, and motion
aspects of our product.

00:25:50.690 --> 00:25:53.640
Now, it's time to talk to users.

00:25:53.640 --> 00:25:56.850
Get some feedback and check
if you're on the right track.

00:25:56.850 --> 00:25:59.880
Also, see if you run
into any major blockers

00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:02.600
you didn't anticipate.

00:26:02.600 --> 00:26:05.360
Consider running a
heuristic evaluation.

00:26:05.360 --> 00:26:08.660
It consists of having a
small set of examiners

00:26:08.660 --> 00:26:13.160
evaluate your app against known
usability principles, otherwise

00:26:13.160 --> 00:26:15.230
called heuristics.

00:26:15.230 --> 00:26:17.960
So right here, we have three
heuristics from the material

00:26:17.960 --> 00:26:23.110
design accessibility
guidelines, and they're clear,

00:26:23.110 --> 00:26:25.980
they're robust, and specific.

00:26:25.980 --> 00:26:27.620
So let's check.

00:26:27.620 --> 00:26:32.330
Is your app clear, meaning
are its layouts non-crowded,

00:26:32.330 --> 00:26:35.330
and are its calls-to-action
visually distinct?

00:26:35.330 --> 00:26:37.250
Is your app robust?

00:26:37.250 --> 00:26:41.120
Does it support a variety
of user capabilities?

00:26:41.120 --> 00:26:43.710
Finally, is your app specific?

00:26:43.710 --> 00:26:47.630
Does it specifically support
a variety of user technologies

00:26:47.630 --> 00:26:51.080
in the ways that
the user expects?

00:26:51.080 --> 00:26:52.910
Let's try this out with Crane.

00:26:52.910 --> 00:26:55.790
So here, we have two
button variations,

00:26:55.790 --> 00:27:01.740
and we want to see if it's clear
enough for low-vision users.

00:27:01.740 --> 00:27:05.250
Well, we may find that
these two buttons actually

00:27:05.250 --> 00:27:07.710
have the same color contrast.

00:27:07.710 --> 00:27:12.690
But we may also find that people
prefer the one on the right,

00:27:12.690 --> 00:27:17.130
because the shopping cart icon
makes the purpose of the button

00:27:17.130 --> 00:27:23.560
more obvious for people with
and without disabilities.

00:27:23.560 --> 00:27:25.600
After you're completing
your product,

00:27:25.600 --> 00:27:28.390
conduct a heuristics
evaluation, and feel

00:27:28.390 --> 00:27:31.270
free to use the accessibility
guidelines provided

00:27:31.270 --> 00:27:33.430
by material design.

00:27:33.430 --> 00:27:38.600
Is your app clear,
robust, and specific?

00:27:38.600 --> 00:27:42.531
Now, back to Bethany on
how to develop your app.

00:27:42.531 --> 00:27:43.864
BETHANY FONG: Thanks, Catherine.

00:27:43.864 --> 00:27:47.217
[APPLAUSE]

00:27:48.180 --> 00:27:50.810
So you've moved on to
the development stage.

00:27:50.810 --> 00:27:53.310
And you'll want to make sure
that all of those decisions you

00:27:53.310 --> 00:27:55.490
just made in the
design stage pull

00:27:55.490 --> 00:27:58.670
through to the final product.

00:27:58.670 --> 00:28:01.150
So the first thing you can
do is use standard components

00:28:01.150 --> 00:28:02.590
when designing.

00:28:02.590 --> 00:28:05.650
If you use material components,
that will be pre-vetted,

00:28:05.650 --> 00:28:08.180
work well within a
holistic design system,

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:11.480
and they'll be usable and
recognizable to your users.

00:28:11.480 --> 00:28:13.522
If you do something
nonstandard, note

00:28:13.522 --> 00:28:15.730
that you'll perhaps have to
design the full component

00:28:15.730 --> 00:28:17.779
yourself, as well
as marking it up

00:28:17.779 --> 00:28:20.320
with the appropriate metadata,
particularly for screen reader

00:28:20.320 --> 00:28:21.220
users.

00:28:21.220 --> 00:28:26.160
You'll need to provide labels,
structure, and traversal paths.

00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:28.230
And designers, one
tool that you can use

00:28:28.230 --> 00:28:30.540
is Gallery, created
by Google to help

00:28:30.540 --> 00:28:34.020
you manage design iterations
and get quick design feedback.

00:28:34.020 --> 00:28:35.790
If you use our
material theme editor

00:28:35.790 --> 00:28:38.190
with Sketch, which is
a popular design tool,

00:28:38.190 --> 00:28:40.350
and upload your
mocks to Gallery,

00:28:40.350 --> 00:28:43.620
you'll automatically see all
measurements, or red lines,

00:28:43.620 --> 00:28:45.400
as designers call them.

00:28:45.400 --> 00:28:49.212
For example, you can see here
how large this price text is

00:28:49.212 --> 00:28:50.670
and make sure that
the touch target

00:28:50.670 --> 00:28:53.550
size is going to be large
enough to be tappable for people

00:28:53.550 --> 00:28:55.230
with hand tremor.

00:28:55.230 --> 00:28:57.300
You can also use it to
communicate back and forth

00:28:57.300 --> 00:28:59.640
with your team about
accessibility markup

00:28:59.640 --> 00:29:02.430
and any verbalizations
or UX writing

00:29:02.430 --> 00:29:05.310
that you might want to do.

00:29:05.310 --> 00:29:07.470
And don't forget to
use scalable text.

00:29:07.470 --> 00:29:09.900
This allows for a piece of
text to scale up or down,

00:29:09.900 --> 00:29:12.330
according to the user's
individual settings.

00:29:12.330 --> 00:29:14.580
This is really important
for users with low vision

00:29:14.580 --> 00:29:16.530
who may have large
text turned on,

00:29:16.530 --> 00:29:19.830
but usually, the rest of the
UI remains the same size.

00:29:19.830 --> 00:29:22.350
So follow the specific
platform standards

00:29:22.350 --> 00:29:25.352
for how scalable text
should be implemented.

00:29:25.352 --> 00:29:27.810
And here's the same screen with
the large text now rendered

00:29:27.810 --> 00:29:28.650
correctly.

00:29:28.650 --> 00:29:31.946
You can actually read
it, which is great.

00:29:31.946 --> 00:29:35.320
So engineers, you can keep
users with various impairments

00:29:35.320 --> 00:29:38.560
in mind as you code, just as
a designer would periodically

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:41.110
consider a user with
low vision, no vision,

00:29:41.110 --> 00:29:43.000
or some mobility challenges.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:45.070
And one way of
focusing this work

00:29:45.070 --> 00:29:46.900
is to schedule
periodic bug bashes

00:29:46.900 --> 00:29:50.914
and fix-its from a specifically
accessibility point of view.

00:29:50.914 --> 00:29:52.330
And there's also
a number of tools

00:29:52.330 --> 00:29:53.800
that you can use
during development

00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:56.890
to check your accessibility
on web and on Android.

00:29:56.890 --> 00:29:58.750
These include
Accessibility Scanner

00:29:58.750 --> 00:30:01.120
on Android, which is the
app shown here, which

00:30:01.120 --> 00:30:04.030
is really easy to use,
because it checks your app

00:30:04.030 --> 00:30:07.420
screen by screen for any
accessibility errors.

00:30:07.420 --> 00:30:09.970
And come by the Accessibility
Sandbox during I/O

00:30:09.970 --> 00:30:13.350
to speak for engineers to
learn about other dev tools

00:30:13.350 --> 00:30:17.140
that you can use during
your own process.

00:30:17.140 --> 00:30:18.810
So as you're
developing, don't forget

00:30:18.810 --> 00:30:22.080
to use common components
when you can and just inherit

00:30:22.080 --> 00:30:24.600
the work that we've
already done for you there.

00:30:24.600 --> 00:30:28.650
Use scalable text, and use
accessibility development tools

00:30:28.650 --> 00:30:33.600
throughout your process to
check yourself as you go.

00:30:33.600 --> 00:30:36.070
All right.

00:30:36.070 --> 00:30:37.720
ANDREA WONG: Thanks, Bethany.

00:30:37.720 --> 00:30:42.010
So now, I'm going to talk about
the last stage, stage four,

00:30:42.010 --> 00:30:43.800
after development.

00:30:43.800 --> 00:30:47.130
At this point, the bulk of your
development work is complete,

00:30:47.130 --> 00:30:48.300
and you're about to launch.

00:30:54.470 --> 00:30:58.520
At this time, we recommend using
a tool like Pre-Launch Report

00:30:58.520 --> 00:31:00.350
from the Google Play Store.

00:31:00.350 --> 00:31:03.170
Some of you may already be
using Pre-Launch Report,

00:31:03.170 --> 00:31:06.260
but the good news is, it
now includes accessibility.

00:31:06.260 --> 00:31:09.710
So upload your app to
alpha or beta channel,

00:31:09.710 --> 00:31:12.950
and it'll crawl through your
app to identify a number of ways

00:31:12.950 --> 00:31:19.320
to improve it, like crashes,
latency issues, and, of course,

00:31:19.320 --> 00:31:20.790
accessibility.

00:31:20.790 --> 00:31:23.910
And you won't need to instrument
your app ahead of time.

00:31:23.910 --> 00:31:28.170
For the web, we recommend
automated accessibility tools

00:31:28.170 --> 00:31:31.410
that's built right into
our Chrome DevTools.

00:31:31.410 --> 00:31:33.390
So inside the
Audits panel, you'll

00:31:33.390 --> 00:31:35.590
see a tool called Lighthouse.

00:31:35.590 --> 00:31:39.090
Lighthouse will run
about 40 automated tests

00:31:39.090 --> 00:31:42.990
against your site to check for
common accessibility issues.

00:31:42.990 --> 00:31:46.300
When it's finished,
it'll give you a score.

00:31:46.300 --> 00:31:48.330
It'll point out the
failing elements.

00:31:48.330 --> 00:31:51.120
And the best part is, it'll
link you to documentation

00:31:51.120 --> 00:31:55.312
with instructions on how to
fix those failing elements.

00:31:55.312 --> 00:31:57.520
And if you've done everything
right up to this point,

00:31:57.520 --> 00:31:59.800
if you've listened to all
of us, then everything here

00:31:59.800 --> 00:32:03.080
should be a breeze.

00:32:03.080 --> 00:32:06.320
One more thing-- no great
onboarding experience

00:32:06.320 --> 00:32:09.680
is complete without
good help content.

00:32:09.680 --> 00:32:13.400
And help content is a resource
that people with disabilities

00:32:13.400 --> 00:32:15.590
often utilize.

00:32:15.590 --> 00:32:19.730
So make sure you include in
help content on accessibility,

00:32:19.730 --> 00:32:23.700
and make sure that content
is actually accessible.

00:32:23.700 --> 00:32:27.270
This is a great opportunity
to help all users get off

00:32:27.270 --> 00:32:30.720
to a great start with
your app or your product

00:32:30.720 --> 00:32:32.610
and recover quickly
when they get stuck.

00:32:35.170 --> 00:32:37.100
Yay, you've launched.

00:32:37.100 --> 00:32:38.810
Now that we're here,
you're probably

00:32:38.810 --> 00:32:41.780
going through your
metrics, your analytics.

00:32:41.780 --> 00:32:44.520
You're checking the
effectiveness of your launch,

00:32:44.520 --> 00:32:47.150
the user engagement,
and so forth.

00:32:47.150 --> 00:32:50.000
You're hopefully also
doing user studies,

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.160
and you're measuring
satisfaction

00:32:52.160 --> 00:32:55.550
to see how well your app is
being received by everyone.

00:32:55.550 --> 00:32:58.370
At this point, include
respondents with accessibility

00:32:58.370 --> 00:33:02.110
needs so that you're
hearing all the feedback.

00:33:02.110 --> 00:33:06.220
This is also the perfect
time to stop and understand

00:33:06.220 --> 00:33:09.160
what benefits your team has
reaped from design inclusively

00:33:09.160 --> 00:33:11.060
from the very beginning.

00:33:11.060 --> 00:33:13.690
So here, do a post-mortem.

00:33:13.690 --> 00:33:17.500
Decide what to cut, what
to keep, what to change,

00:33:17.500 --> 00:33:19.860
and apply that to
your next cycle.

00:33:19.860 --> 00:33:23.300
Over time design inclusive will
become second nature to you.

00:33:25.990 --> 00:33:28.110
Let's go over the main points.

00:33:28.110 --> 00:33:30.780
One, check for common
accessibility issues

00:33:30.780 --> 00:33:32.610
with Pre-Launch
Report and Lighthouse

00:33:32.610 --> 00:33:34.860
and countless other
tools out there.

00:33:34.860 --> 00:33:38.760
Make sure you have accessibility
help content that's accessible.

00:33:38.760 --> 00:33:42.540
And get feedback from
users with disabilities.

00:33:42.540 --> 00:33:45.750
And now, Jen will
summarize all this for us.

00:33:45.750 --> 00:33:47.730
JEN DEVINS: Thank you, Andrea.

00:33:47.730 --> 00:33:52.120
All right, so there you have
it, our tool kit of ideas

00:33:52.120 --> 00:33:55.960
that, hopefully, you can
apply to your process.

00:33:55.960 --> 00:33:58.690
We know it's a lot
of information.

00:33:58.690 --> 00:34:02.010
There's a lot of great resources
out there that you can rely on.

00:34:02.010 --> 00:34:05.130
We wanted to leave
you with one thing

00:34:05.130 --> 00:34:11.159
you can do during each stage
of the process starting today.

00:34:11.159 --> 00:34:13.020
So if you're starting
out and you're

00:34:13.020 --> 00:34:16.500
defining your product vision,
can't stress it enough--

00:34:16.500 --> 00:34:19.139
get out there and talk to users.

00:34:19.139 --> 00:34:21.120
If you're curious
of, where should I

00:34:21.120 --> 00:34:22.530
find users with disabilities?

00:34:22.530 --> 00:34:23.880
I don't know anyone.

00:34:23.880 --> 00:34:27.834
There's lots of organizations
nationally and internationally

00:34:27.834 --> 00:34:30.000
that you can reach out to,
and they'll often put you

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:32.130
in contact with their members.

00:34:32.130 --> 00:34:35.790
And in fact, today in the
Design and Accessibility Sandbox

00:34:35.790 --> 00:34:38.520
across the way, there are
members from the National

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:41.010
Federation of the
Blind that are willing

00:34:41.010 --> 00:34:46.540
and wanting to give you feedback
or just answer your questions.

00:34:46.540 --> 00:34:49.510
If you're in the design
stage, you probably

00:34:49.510 --> 00:34:52.580
started working on your
interaction workflow model,

00:34:52.580 --> 00:34:54.969
and you're thinking about
it, have it drafted.

00:34:54.969 --> 00:34:59.380
Before you get too far, take
a step back and think, now,

00:34:59.380 --> 00:35:02.254
how would a user that's
using just a keyboard

00:35:02.254 --> 00:35:03.670
go through this
interaction model?

00:35:03.670 --> 00:35:05.890
How would they get
their task done?

00:35:05.890 --> 00:35:07.990
This is a great place
to start, and you'll

00:35:07.990 --> 00:35:13.670
be very happy you did
this earlier than later.

00:35:13.670 --> 00:35:18.380
If you're in the development
stage, use standard components.

00:35:18.380 --> 00:35:21.200
They've been
stress-test, and they're

00:35:21.200 --> 00:35:23.280
familiar to users,
which is great.

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:25.730
You don't want users
to have to relearn

00:35:25.730 --> 00:35:30.130
their app for each screen.

00:35:30.130 --> 00:35:33.310
And finally, if you're
nearing that finish line

00:35:33.310 --> 00:35:36.950
and it's after development,
just as Andrea mentioned,

00:35:36.950 --> 00:35:39.460
we really recommend
ensuring that you

00:35:39.460 --> 00:35:42.970
have accessible onboarding
and help content

00:35:42.970 --> 00:35:44.650
and, if it makes
sense for your app,

00:35:44.650 --> 00:35:48.940
to have accessibility-focused
tutorials and onboarding

00:35:48.940 --> 00:35:49.440
material.

00:35:52.940 --> 00:35:56.400
Making inclusive
products is critical.

00:35:56.400 --> 00:35:59.840
We all have the power
and responsibility

00:35:59.840 --> 00:36:03.920
to remove barriers
and empower all users

00:36:03.920 --> 00:36:07.720
to be productive and connected.

